{
  "Half-life is the time it takes for:": "",
  "A sample to double in amount": "",
  "Half of a radioactive sample to decay": "",
  "A reaction to reach full completion": "",
  "All of a sample to completely decay": "",
  "Half-life is the time required for half of the atoms in a radioactive sample to decay. After one half-life, 50% of the original sample remains. The process continues with each half-life reducing the remaining amount by half.": "",
  "After 2 half-lives, what fraction of the original sample remains?": "",
  "1/2 of the original remains": "",
  "1/4 of the original remains": "",
  "1/8 of the original remains": "",
  "1/16 of the original remains": "",
  "After each half-life, the remaining fraction is halved. After 1 half-life: 1/2. After 2 half-lives: 1/2 x 1/2 = 1/4. The general formula is (1/2)^n, where n is the number of half-lives that have passed.": "",
  "After 3 half-lives, what fraction remains?": "",
  "1/3 of the original remains": "",
  "After 3 half-lives, the fraction remaining = (1/2)^3 = 1/8. Each half-life cuts the previous amount in half: 1 -> 1/2 -> 1/4 -> 1/8. Note that 1/3 is incorrect because the fraction is always a power of 1/2, not 1/n.": "",
  "If a sample has a half-life of 10 years, after 30 years:": "",
  "None of the sample remains": "",
  "1/8 of the sample remains": "",
  "1/16 of the sample remains": "",
  "1/4 of the sample remains": "",
  "First, find the number of half-lives: 30 years / 10 years per half-life = 3 half-lives. Then calculate the remaining fraction: (1/2)^3 = 1/8. So 1/8 of the original sample remains after 30 years. A radioactive sample never fully reaches zero.": "",
  "Carbon-14 has a half-life of approximately:": "",
  "1 million years": "",
  "5,730 years": "",
  "24 hours": "",
  "100 years": "",
  "Carbon-14 has a half-life of approximately 5,730 years. This makes it useful for dating organic materials up to about 50,000 years old. Living organisms constantly replenish C-14, but after death the C-14 decays, allowing scientists to determine the age.": "",
  "The half-life formula is:": "",
  "N = N0 x (1/2)^(t/t1/2)": "",
  "N = N0 / t": "",
  "N = N0 x t1/2": "",
  "N = N0 x 2^t": "",
  "The half-life formula N = N0 x (1/2)^(t/t1/2) calculates the remaining amount (N) from the initial amount (N0), where t is the elapsed time and t1/2 is the half-life. The exponent t/t1/2 gives the number of half-lives that have passed.": "",
  "Half-life is independent of:": "",
  "The nuclear forces within the isotope": "",
  "The passage of time during the decay": "",
  "The specific type of radioactive isotope": "",
  "The amount of sample or external conditions": "",
  "Half-life is a constant property of each radioactive isotope and does not change based on the amount of sample, temperature, pressure, or other external conditions. Whether you have 1 gram or 1 kilogram, the half-life remains the same.": "",
  "After 4 half-lives, what fraction of the original radioactive sample remains?": "",
  "1/4 of the original sample remains": "",
  "1/16 of the original sample remains": "",
  "1/8 of the original sample remains": "",
  "1/32 of the original sample remains": "",
  "After 4 half-lives, the fraction remaining = (1/2)^4 = 1/16. Following the pattern: 1/2 -> 1/4 -> 1/8 -> 1/16. This means only 6.25% of the original radioactive material is still present.": "",
  "A radioactive isotope has a half-life of 6 hours. If you start with 80 grams, how much remains after 18 hours?": "",
  "20 grams of the isotope remains": "",
  "40 grams of the isotope remains": "",
  "10 grams of the isotope remains": "",
  "5 grams of the isotope remains": "",
  "Number of half-lives = 18 hours / 6 hours = 3 half-lives. Remaining amount = 80 x (1/2)^3 = 80 x 1/8 = 10 grams. Step by step: 80 -> 40 -> 20 -> 10 grams.": "",
  "If 100 grams of a radioactive sample decays to 12.5 grams, how many half-lives have passed?": "",
  "2 half-lives have passed": "",
  "4 half-lives have passed": "",
  "5 half-lives have passed": "",
  "3 half-lives have passed": "",
  "Starting with 100 g: after 1 half-life = 50 g, after 2 = 25 g, after 3 = 12.5 g. So 3 half-lives have passed. You can also solve this using the formula: 12.5/100 = 1/8 = (1/2)^3, so n = 3.": "",
  "What is a half-life?": "",
  "The time required for half of the atoms in a radioactive sample to undergo decay": "",
  "The time required for all of the atoms in a radioactive sample to fully decay": "",
  "The amount of energy released when half of a radioactive sample undergoes fission": "",
  "The mass of radioactive material needed to sustain a nuclear chain reaction": "",
  "A half-life is the time required for exactly half of the radioactive atoms in a sample to undergo radioactive decay. It is a constant characteristic of each isotope. After each half-life, the remaining amount is halved.": "",
  "What does the variable N0 represent in the half-life formula N = N0 x (1/2)^(t/t1/2)?": "",
  "The number of half-lives that have elapsed since the sample began decaying": "",
  "The initial amount of radioactive material present before any decay has occurred": "",
  "The final amount of radioactive material remaining after a given period of time": "",
  "The half-life of the radioactive isotope measured in units of time": "",
  "In the half-life formula, N0 (N-zero or N-naught) represents the initial amount of radioactive material before any decay has occurred. N is the amount remaining after time t, and t1/2 is the half-life.": "",
  "Define 'radioactive decay rate.'": "",
  "The speed at which radioactive particles travel through a material or vacuum": "",
  "The total mass of radioactive material that decays during a single half-life period": "",
  "The number of decay events (disintegrations) that occur per unit of time in a sample": "",
  "The distance that radiation can travel before being absorbed by shielding material": "",
  "The radioactive decay rate (also called activity) is the number of nuclear disintegrations that occur per unit of time. It is measured in units like becquerels (decays per second) or curies. The decay rate decreases as the sample decays, since fewer radioactive atoms remain.": "",
  "What does 'exponential decay' mean in the context of radioactive half-life?": "",
  "The sample decays at a constant rate, losing the same mass every time period": "",
  "The sample decays faster and faster as time goes on until it is completely gone": "",
  "The sample stops decaying after a certain number of half-lives have passed": "",
  "The remaining amount decreases by a constant fraction (one-half) in each equal time interval": "",
  "Exponential decay means the amount decreases by a constant fraction (not a constant amount) in each equal time interval. For radioactive decay, half the remaining amount decays during each half-life. This produces a characteristic curve that approaches but never reaches zero.": "",
  "What is meant by 'radiometric dating'?": "",
  "A technique that uses the known half-life of radioactive isotopes to determine the age of materials": "",
  "A method of measuring the radiation exposure of workers in nuclear power plant facilities": "",
  "A process of using radiation to sterilize medical equipment and preserve food products": "",
  "A technique that measures the speed of radioactive particles emitted during nuclear decay": "",
  "Radiometric dating uses the predictable rate of radioactive decay to determine the age of materials. By measuring the ratio of parent isotope to daughter isotope, scientists can calculate how many half-lives have passed and determine the sample's age.": "",
  "What is a 'decay curve'?": "",
  "A straight line showing the constant rate at which a radioactive sample loses mass": "",
  "A graph showing the exponential decrease of a radioactive sample over time": "",
  "A circular diagram showing the different types of radioactive decay processes": "",
  "A table listing the half-lives of all known radioactive isotopes by element": "",
  "A decay curve is a graph that plots the amount of radioactive material remaining (y-axis) against time (x-axis). It shows a characteristic exponential decrease — steep at first, then gradually flattening out as less and less material remains to decay.": "",
  "What does it mean that half-life is a 'statistical' property?": "",
  "It means that half-life values are only approximate guesses that scientists have made": "",
  "It means that the half-life changes based on how many atoms are in the sample": "",
  "It means we cannot predict when a specific atom will decay, but can predict the behavior of large numbers": "",
  "It means half-life only applies to artificial isotopes created in particle accelerators": "",
  "Radioactive decay is a random process at the individual atom level — we cannot predict exactly when any single atom will decay. However, with a large number of atoms, statistics allow us to predict very accurately that half will decay within one half-life.": "",
  "What is 'carbon-14 dating'?": "",
  "A method of determining the age of rocks by measuring their uranium content": "",
  "A technique for measuring the radioactivity level of food products before sale": "",
  "A process of creating carbon-14 in a laboratory for use in medical imaging scans": "",
  "A radiometric dating method that measures the ratio of C-14 to C-12 to determine the age of organic materials": "",
  "Carbon-14 dating measures the ratio of radioactive C-14 to stable C-12 in once-living materials. Living organisms maintain a constant C-14/C-12 ratio, but after death C-14 decays with a half-life of 5,730 years. By measuring how much C-14 remains, scientists can determine when the organism died.": "",
  "Define 'parent isotope' and 'daughter isotope' in radioactive decay.": "",
  "The parent is the original radioactive isotope; the daughter is the product isotope formed after decay": "",
  "The parent is the stable product; the daughter is the original radioactive isotope that decayed": "",
  "The parent is the heavier isotope; the daughter is always a lighter isotope of the same element": "",
  "The parent and daughter refer to two isotopes that have the same half-life values": "",
  "In radioactive decay, the parent isotope is the original unstable radioactive isotope that undergoes decay. The daughter isotope is the new isotope (or element) produced as a result of the decay. For example, C-14 (parent) decays to N-14 (daughter).": "",
  "What does the exponent (t/t1/2) represent in the half-life formula?": "",
  "The total mass of the radioactive sample divided by its atomic mass number": "",
  "The number of half-lives that have elapsed during the time period t": "",
  "The ratio of the daughter isotope to the parent isotope in the sample": "",
  "The fraction of the original sample that has already undergone decay": "",
  "In the formula N = N0 x (1/2)^(t/t1/2), the exponent t/t1/2 represents the number of half-lives that have passed. For example, if the half-life is 10 years and 30 years have elapsed, then t/t1/2 = 30/10 = 3 half-lives.": "",
  "A forensic scientist finds a bone fragment at an archaeological site. The C-14 content is 1/4 of what it would be in a living organism. Approximately how old is the bone?": "",
  "About 5,730 years old (one half-life of C-14)": "",
  "About 17,190 years old (three half-lives of C-14)": "",
  "About 11,460 years old (two half-lives of C-14)": "",
  "About 22,920 years old (four half-lives of C-14)": "",
  "If 1/4 of the original C-14 remains, then 2 half-lives have passed (since 1/2 x 1/2 = 1/4). The half-life of C-14 is 5,730 years, so the bone is approximately 2 x 5,730 = 11,460 years old.": "",
  "A hospital receives a 200-gram shipment of a radioactive isotope with a half-life of 8 hours. The isotope must be used while at least 25 grams remain. How much time does the hospital have?": "",
  "16 hours, which is two half-lives": "",
  "8 hours, which is one half-life": "",
  "32 hours, which is four half-lives": "",
  "24 hours, which is three half-lives": "",
  "Starting with 200 g: after 8 hours (1 half-life) = 100 g, after 16 hours (2 half-lives) = 50 g, after 24 hours (3 half-lives) = 25 g. The hospital has 24 hours before the amount drops below 25 grams.": "",
  "A student plots a graph of a radioactive sample over time and observes the amount decreasing. After 20 minutes, 50 grams remain from an original 200 grams. What is the half-life of this isotope?": "",
  "5 minutes per half-life": "",
  "10 minutes per half-life": "",
  "15 minutes per half-life": "",
  "20 minutes per half-life": "",
  "From 200 g to 50 g: 200 -> 100 -> 50. That is 2 half-lives. If 2 half-lives took 20 minutes, then 1 half-life = 20/2 = 10 minutes. You can verify: (1/2)^2 = 1/4, and 200 x 1/4 = 50 g.": "",
  "A nuclear waste facility must store radioactive waste until it decays to 1/32 of its original activity. If the waste has a half-life of 100 years, how long must it be stored?": "",
  "300 years, which is 3 half-lives": "",
  "400 years, which is 4 half-lives": "",
  "600 years, which is 6 half-lives": "",
  "500 years, which is 5 half-lives": "",
  "1/32 = (1/2)^5, so 5 half-lives must pass. With a half-life of 100 years: 5 x 100 = 500 years. Step by step: 1/2 -> 1/4 -> 1/8 -> 1/16 -> 1/32 (five halvings).": "",
  "A scientist has two radioactive samples: Sample A has a half-life of 2 days and Sample B has a half-life of 20 days. After 10 days, which statement is correct?": "",
  "Both samples have decayed by the same fraction since they started at the same time": "",
  "Sample B has decayed more because longer half-lives mean faster decay rates overall": "",
  "Sample A has decayed much more because it has gone through 5 half-lives while Sample B has only completed about half of one half-life": "",
  "Neither sample has decayed at all because 10 days is not enough time for decay": "",
  "Sample A: 10 days / 2 days = 5 half-lives, so (1/2)^5 = 1/32 remains (about 3.1%). Sample B: 10 days / 20 days = 0.5 half-lives, so (1/2)^0.5 = about 70.7% remains. Sample A has decayed far more than Sample B.": "",
  "A pharmacist receives 120 mg of a radioactive tracer with a half-life of 4 hours. A patient needs a 15 mg dose. What is the latest time the dose can be administered?": "",
  "8 hours after receiving the tracer": "",
  "16 hours after receiving the tracer": "",
  "4 hours after receiving the tracer": "",
  "12 hours after receiving the tracer": "",
  "Starting with 120 mg: after 4 hours = 60 mg, after 8 hours = 30 mg, after 12 hours = 15 mg. At 12 hours (3 half-lives), exactly 15 mg remains. After that, there would not be enough for the required dose.": "",
  "A geologist finds a rock sample where 75% of the original uranium-238 has decayed into lead-206. How many half-lives have passed?": "",
  "1 half-life has passed (50% would have decayed)": "",
  "2 half-lives have passed (75% has decayed, 25% remains)": "",
  "3 half-lives have passed (87.5% would have decayed)": "",
  "4 half-lives have passed (93.75% would have decayed)": "",
  "If 75% has decayed, then 25% (or 1/4) of the original uranium remains. Since 1/4 = (1/2)^2, exactly 2 half-lives have passed. After 1 half-life, 50% remains; after 2, 25% remains; after 3, 12.5% remains.": "",
  "A student is given a 400-gram radioactive sample and told that after 5 half-lives, only 12.5 grams remain. The student says this is wrong. Is the student correct?": "",
  "The student is wrong; 12.5 grams is the correct amount remaining after 5 half-lives": "",
  "The student is correct; 25 grams should remain after 5 half-lives of the sample": "",
  "The student is correct; none of the sample should remain after 5 half-lives": "",
  "The student is correct; 50 grams should remain after 5 half-lives of the sample": "",
  "400 x (1/2)^5 = 400 x 1/32 = 12.5 grams. The calculation is correct: 400 -> 200 -> 100 -> 50 -> 25 -> 12.5. The student is wrong; 12.5 grams is indeed the correct remaining amount after 5 half-lives.": "",
  "A teacher asks: 'If a radioactive sample has been decaying for 10 half-lives, is it safe to say the sample is completely gone?' What is the correct answer?": "",
  "Yes, after 10 half-lives all radioactive atoms have completely decayed to nothing": "",
  "Yes, after 5 half-lives the sample is considered gone, so 10 is well past that point": "",
  "No, about 1/1024 of the original sample still remains, though the amount is very small": "",
  "No, half-life decay reverses direction after 10 cycles and the sample begins growing": "",
  "After 10 half-lives, (1/2)^10 = 1/1024 (about 0.1%) of the original sample remains. Theoretically, a radioactive sample never reaches exactly zero — it just becomes immeasurably small. After 10 half-lives, the remaining activity is negligible but not zero.": "",
  "An environmental scientist is monitoring a radioactive spill. The isotope has a half-life of 30 years. The area will be declared safe when activity drops to 1/8 of current levels. How many years until the area is safe?": "",
  "30 years from the current date": "",
  "60 years from the current date": "",
  "120 years from the current date": "",
  "90 years from the current date": "",
  "To reach 1/8 of the current level: 1/8 = (1/2)^3, so 3 half-lives must pass. With a half-life of 30 years: 3 x 30 = 90 years. The area would be declared safe after 90 years.": ""
}